tion of psychotropic drugs -- tPart IV. NEW SUBJECTIVITIES, SOCIALITIES, AND THE MEDIA -- t11. New forms of sociality on the Internet. Users, advocates, and opponents of self-medication -- t12. 'The Internet saved my life'. Overcoming isolation among the homebound chronically ill -- tList of Contributors -- tAcknowledgements -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThe landscape of health care is changing rapidly, both on an organizational and a technological level. This book gathers medical anthropologists to examine the ways that both patients and health care workers are being affected by new policies, market, and technologies. Contributors cover a wide range of topics, including vaccination, disability, migration, and self-medication, making clear that not only are changing circumstances leading to the emergence of new socialities, but they are also driving new ethics and moralities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 7aMEDICAL / General.2bisacsh1 aHardon, Anita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHadolt, Bernhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLudvigsen, Bodil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaxaire, Claudie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraf, Franz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHadolt, Bernhard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHardon, Anita, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aQuaranta, Ivo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat